===== non cogitatur non esse =====
[: not thought of therefore not existing :]

    (p. 7) Precisely because causation does capture a time-oriented relation, it
    can only depend on the single source of time orientation that is compatible
    with physics: the thermodynamic arrow of time.

The only reason given for thinking that the direction of the arrow of time is
determined by the entropy gradient (i.e. the future is by definition the
temporal direction in which entropy increases) is that the author cannot think
of an alternative that is compatible with the laws of physics.

But there are of course at least two alternatives: (1) Either there are
time asymmetric physical laws that we haven't discovered yet. Laws that might,
among other things, explain _why_ entropy is always increasing (overall). OR (2)
there might be something compatible with the laws of physics that we haven't
yet considered.

This is by far the weakest part of the paper.
